{
  "doc_id": "54138",
  "text": "Thus, there will be no randomized trial evidence for CACbased prevention strategies in the near term. Therefore, there is a critical need for alternative strategies evaluating the impact of CAC testing, as well as other risk-based novel biomarkers (eg, high-sensitivity C reactive protein [hs-CRP]), particularly in real-world settings. One such strategy is the use of propensity-based matching to convert observational data into a form more akin to randomized controlled trial data by mimicking the effect of randomization. [CITATION_1] Using observed covariates, propensity scores match subjects who receive an intervention (eg, CAC) with subjects who do not to balance the distribution of potential confounders of the outcome (eg, ASCVD events) in both groups. [CITATION_2] However, unlike randomization, this strategy cannot balance unmeasured confounders.",
